	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1R"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Baltimore</placeName> <date>July 22d 1849</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Dr Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Perceiving from the Occident<lb/> that several congregations are in want of Readers or<lb/> Hazans&#44; I may probably be aiding their wishes by<lb/> communicating to you that from a letter lately received<lb/> by my Mother from <placeName>England</placeName>&#44; we learn that a brother<lb/> of the <persName>Revd Mr Isaacs</persName> of <placeName>New York</placeName> is about visiting the<lb/> <placeName>U. States</placeName>&#44; and with a view perhaps to an engage&#45;<lb/>ment as Hazan&#8212;By way therefore of information<lb/> in such a way as you may deem fit to mention it&#44; I<lb/> have extracted that portion of the letter referred to&#44; which<lb/> is annexed&#8212;I should be gratified should it result<lb/> beneficially to the parties interested.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With the best regards of our family&#44; I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">Dear sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)">Yours with great respect</p>
			<p rend="indent(7)"><persName role="author">Mendes Cohen</persName></p>
				<p>&#124;<hi rend="underline">Over</hi>&#124;</p>
			<pb n="1V"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><hi rend="underline">Extract</hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">&#8220;I have now to congratulate you on the proba&#45;<lb/>bility of the <persName>Revd. D. M. Isaacs</persName> going to the <placeName>states</placeName><lb/> he having sent in his resignation as lecturer to the<lb/> <placeName>Liverpool</placeName> congregation.  The reason he has given for so<lb/> doing&#44; is the smallness of the salary&#44; which I can<lb/> readily believe for it is too trifling for a person of his<lb/> acquirements to receive.  Yet disordered as the finan&#45;<lb/>cial affairs of the congregation are I fear there are<lb/> other causes in operation&#59; such as&#44; their want of appreci&#45;<lb/>ation of him&#44; and the division in their councils.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr Isaacs</persName> who I believe has a brother who lec&#45;<lb/>tures in <placeName>N. York</placeName> has been above 12 years amongst us.<lb/>  Educated under the auspices and in the house of our late<lb/> chief Rabbi&#44; he possesses all the energy and learning<lb/> of that eminent divine combined with the elegancies<add>&#63;</add><lb/> of modern literature&#44; and was the first in this coun&#45;<lb/>try&#44; who dared to turn aside from the beaten track&#44;<lb/> and enlighten us with sermons in the vernacular<lb/> tongue.  I shall sincerely regret his departure.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">But merit seems to turn to the best to be appre&#45;<lb/>ciated&#58; and I have no doubt he will be eagerly<lb/> sought after in the <placeName>States</placeName>.&#8221;</p>
				<p rend="The following number is written in pencil at the bottom of the page."><date>7&#45;22&#45;1829</date></p>
			<pb n="2V"/>
